{"title_page": "Punjab Institute of Mental Health", "text_new": "{{short description|Psychiatric facility in Lahore, Pakistan}}\n{{short description|Psychiatric facility in Pakistan}}\n'''Punjab Institute of Mental Health''' is an institute situated in [[Lahore|Lahore, Pakistan]]. It is the largest psychiatric facility in [[South Asia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pimh.gop.pk/about_PIMH.htm|title=::: Punjab Institute of Mental Health :::|website=www.pimh.gop.pk|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref> Solid waste disposal system lacks immensely. Garbage is burnt on a daily bases releasing toxic chemicals in the air.\n\n== History ==\n[[Johann Martin Honigberger]] was a Hungarian doctor who was the doctor of [[Ranjit Singh|Maharaja Ranjit Singh]] from 1812 until Maharaja's death in 1839. He set up the first psychiatric ward just behind the gunpowder factory and started treating more patients after the Maharaja's death. He left for Europe when the East India Company annexed Punjab in 1849. Judicial Commissioner [[Robert Montgomery (colonial administrator)|Robert Montgomery]] took control and decided to build a bigger and secluded facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1423520|title=Hungarian doctor whose caring touch lives on|last=Sheikh|first=Majid|date=2018-07-29|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIt was in 1900 when Lahore Mental Hospital was built in 172 acres of land.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Psychological Impact of the Partition of India|last=Jain|first=Sanjeev|publisher=SAGE Publishing India|year=2018|isbn=978-9352806508|location=|pages=25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Pakistan-hospital-stub}}\n\n{{coord missing|Pakistan}}\n\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Lahore]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Psychiatric facility in Lahore, Pakistan}}\n{{short description|Psychiatric facility in Pakistan}}\n'''Punjab Institute of Mental Health''' is an institute situated in [[Lahore|Lahore, Pakistan]]. It is the largest psychiatric facility in [[South Asia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pimh.gop.pk/about_PIMH.htm|title=::: Punjab Institute of Mental Health :::|website=www.pimh.gop.pk|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[Johann Martin Honigberger]] was a Hungarian doctor who was the doctor of [[Ranjit Singh|Maharaja Ranjit Singh]] from 1812 until Maharaja's death in 1839. He set up the first psychiatric ward just behind the gunpowder factory and started treating more patients after the Maharaja's death. He left for Europe when the East India Company annexed Punjab in 1849. Judicial Commissioner [[Robert Montgomery (colonial administrator)|Robert Montgomery]] took control and decided to build a bigger and secluded facility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1423520|title=Hungarian doctor whose caring touch lives on|last=Sheikh|first=Majid|date=2018-07-29|website=DAWN.COM|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref>\n\nIt was in 1900 when Lahore Mental Hospital was built in 172 acres of land.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Psychological Impact of the Partition of India|last=Jain|first=Sanjeev|publisher=SAGE Publishing India|year=2018|isbn=978-9352806508|location=|pages=25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Pakistan-hospital-stub}}\n\n{{coord missing|Pakistan}}\n\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Lahore]]\n", "name_user": "Umehmood", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punjab_Institute_of_Mental_Health"}
{"title_page": "Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's triple jump", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Men's triple jump\n|games = 1984 Summer\n|venue = [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]]\n|date = 3\u20134 August\n|competitors = 28\n|nations = 21\n|win_value = 17.26\n|win_label = Winning distance\n|longnames = yes\n|gold = [[Al Joyner]]\n|goldNOC = USA\n|silver = [[Mike Conley Sr.|Mike Conley]]\n|silverNOC = USA\n|bronze = [[Keith Connor]]\n|bronzeNOC = GBR\n|prev = [[Athletics at the 1980 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's triple jump|1980]]\n|next = [[Athletics at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's triple jump|1988]]\n}}\n{{AthleticsAt1984SummerOlympics}}\nThe '''[[Triple jump|Men's Triple Jump]]''' event at the '''[[Athletics at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Summer Olympics]]''' in [[Los Angeles, California]] had an entry list of 28 competitors, with two qualifying groups (28 jumpers) before the final (12) took place on August 4, 1984. The top twelve and ties, and all those reaching 16.60 metres advanced to the final.<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1984/ATH/mens-triple-jump.html |title=Athletics at the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Games: Men's Triple Jump |accessdate=24 December 2017 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==Medalists==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|- \n|{{OlympicGoldMedalist|[[Al Joyner]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicSilverMedalist|[[Mike Conley, Sr.|Mike Conley]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n|{{OlympicBronzeMedalist|[[Keith Connor]]|GBR|1984 Summer}}\n|}\n\n==Abbreviations==\n*''All results shown are in metres''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\" text-align:center; font-size:110%;\" width=\"35%\"\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ccffcc\"| '''Q''' || automatic qualification\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"ddffdd\"| '''q''' || qualification by rank\n|-\n|'''DNS''' || did not start\n|-\n|'''NM''' || no mark\n|-\n|'''OR''' || olympic record\n|-\n|'''WR''' || world re